Linear Models and Their Generalizations

Chapter 3- Part 3: ANCOVA single-factor model

Katia Meziani

Motivation

In many situations, the set of explanatory variables includes both quantitative and qualitative variables. Up to now, we have discussed methods that handle either quantitative or qualitative variables separately. However, since both cases originate from the linear model, it is possible to combine them—this is known as analysis of covariance (ANCOVA). Here, we will focus on a simple example involving one categorical factor and one quantitative variable. The extension of this approach will be explored in practice.

Intima media dataset

We will work throughout this chapter with the Intima Media dataset.

Atherosclerosis is the leading cause of death for men over 35 and women over 45 in most developed countries. It manifests as a thickening and loss of elasticity in the inner walls of the arteries, leading to conditions like myocardial infarction. The arterial wall consists of three layers: the intima, media, and adventitia. The thickness of the intima-media layer is a recognized marker of atherosclerosis. This measurement was taken ultrasonically from a sample of 110 subjects in 1999 at the Bordeaux University Hospital.

1. ANCOVA single-factor model

When the response variable \(Y\) is explained by regressors and one factor, we refer to the model as an ANCOVA single-factor model. In this context, we are modeling a quantitative dependent variable \(Y\) based on a qualitative explanatory variable (or factor) that has \(J \in \mathbb{N}^*\) distinct categories or levels and regressor \(x\). We denote by

  • \(Y_{ij}\) the \(i\)-th observation that corresponds to the \(j\)-th modality of the factor.
  • \(x_{ij}\) the value of the regressor of the \(i\)-th observation having modality \(j\).
  • \(n_{j}\) the number of observations \(Y_{ij}\) associated with the modality \(j\) \(s.t.\): \[ \sum_{j=1}^Jn_{j}=n. \]

📌 The results derived from this model can be easily generalized to ANCOVA models involving three factors, four factors, and so on.

[The plan] Let denote by \(\mathcal{J}=\{1,\cdots,J\}\) and by \(\mathcal{K}=\{1,\cdots,K\}\). The plan is said to be

  • Complete if \(\forall (j,k)\in\mathcal{J}\times\mathcal{K}\), \(n_{jk}\geq 1\),
  • Imcomplete if \(\exists (j,k)\in\mathcal{J}\times\mathcal{K}\), \(n_{jk}=0\),
  • Balanced if \(\forall (j,k)\in\mathcal{J}\times\mathcal{K}\), \(n_{jk}=I=\frac{n}{JK}\).

1.1. Regular Model


Modality 1 ⋯ Modality \(J\)
\(Y_{i1} = \tau_1 + \beta_1 x_{i1} + \epsilon_{i1}\) ⋯ \(Y_{iJ} = \tau_J + \beta_J x_{iJ}+ \epsilon_{iJ}\)


[Regular Model]
We define the linear Gaussian regression model (ANCOVA single-factor model) in its regular form as follows: \[\begin{equation*} \label{eq:Anova1_RM} \tag{Anova1 [RM]} Y_{ij}=\tau_j + \beta_1 x_{ij}+\epsilon{ij},\quad i\in\{1,\ldots,n_j\}, \ j\in\mathcal{J} \end{equation*}\] where \(\epsilon_{ij}\stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim}\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2).\)


📌 Note:

  • This assumption can be checked as explained in the previous chapter.
  • We assume that the regression line varies across the different groups (modalities), meaning that both the intercept \(\tau_j\) and the slope \(\beta_j\) change depending on the group \(j\).

Let’s now express our standard single-factor ANCOVA model in matrix form. To do this, we first define for all \(j \in \mathcal{J}\) the vectors \(\boldsymbol{Y}^j \in \mathbb{R}^{n_j}\), \(\,\boldsymbol{\epsilon}^j \in \mathbb{R}^{n_j}\), \(\,\boldsymbol{\theta}^j \in \mathbb{R}^2\) and the matrices \(\boldsymbol{X}^j\) of size \(n_j\times 2\) such that: \[\boldsymbol{Y}^j = \begin{pmatrix} Y_{1j} \\ \vdots\\ Y_{n_jj} \end{pmatrix},\qquad \boldsymbol{\epsilon}^j = \begin{pmatrix} \epsilon_{1j} \\ \vdots\\ \epsilon_{n_jj} \end{pmatrix},\qquad \boldsymbol{\theta}^j = \begin{pmatrix} \tau_j \\ \beta_j \end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad \boldsymbol{X}^j = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & x_{1j} \\ \vdots & \vdots\\ 1 & x_{n_{j}j} \end{pmatrix}\]

We can now combine these into global vectors and matrices, defining the response vector \(\boldsymbol{Y}\in \mathbb{R}^n\) the error vector \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\in \mathbb{R}^n\) the unknown parameter vector \(\boldsymbol{\theta}\in \mathbb{R}^{2J}\) and the design matrix \(\boldsymbol{X}\) of size \(n \times 2J\):

\[\boldsymbol{Y}= \begin{pmatrix} \boldsymbol{Y}^1 \\ \vdots\\ \boldsymbol{Y}^J \end{pmatrix},\qquad \boldsymbol{\epsilon}= \begin{pmatrix} \boldsymbol{\epsilon}^1 \\ \vdots\\ \boldsymbol{\epsilon}^J \end{pmatrix},\qquad \boldsymbol{\theta}= \begin{pmatrix} \boldsymbol{\theta}^1 \\ \vdots\\ \boldsymbol{\theta}^J \end{pmatrix}\quad\text{and}\quad \boldsymbol{X}= \begin{pmatrix} \boldsymbol{X}^1 & \cdots & 0 \\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\ 0 & \cdots & \boldsymbol{X}^J \end{pmatrix} \]

📌 Note: \(\text{Rank}(\boldsymbol{X})=2J\) and \(\text{Rank}(\boldsymbol{X}^j)=2\), \(\forall j\in\mathcal{J}\),indicating that \(\boldsymbol{X}\) and \(\boldsymbol{X}^j\) have full rank.

Therefore, our model can be expressed as:

[Regular Model]
We define the linear Gaussian regression model (ANCOVA single-factor model) in its regular matrix form as follows: \[\begin{equation} \label{eq:ANcOVA1_RM} \tag{ANcOVA 1 [RM]} \boldsymbol{Y}=\boldsymbol{X}\boldsymbol{\theta}+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}, \end{equation}\] where \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\sim\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{0}_n,\sigma^2\mathbf{I}_n)\)

Moreover \[\begin{equation*} \boldsymbol{Y}^j=\boldsymbol{X}^j\boldsymbol{\theta}^j+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}^j, \end{equation*}\] where \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}^j\sim\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{0}_{n_j},\sigma^2\mathbf{I}_{n_j})\), \(\forall j\in\mathcal{J}\).


1.2. Singular Model

From the regular model \(Y_{ij} = \tau_j + \beta_j x_{ij} + \epsilon_{ij}\), consider the following decomposition of \(\tau_j + \beta_j x_{ij}\): \[\forall\;j\in\mathcal{J},\quad \tau_j+ \beta_j x_{ij}=(\mu + \alpha_j) + (b + c_j) x_{ij}, \] where:

  • \(\mu\): the reference intercept (overall mean or baseline intercept).
  • \(\mu + \alpha_j\): the intercept of cell \(j\), with \(\alpha_j\) representing the deviation of cell \(j\)’s intercept from the reference.
  • \(b\): the reference slope (baseline slope).
  • \(b + c_j\): the slope for cell \(j\), where \(c_j\) represents the deviation of cell \(j\)’s slope from the reference slope.

Modality 1 ⋯ Modality \(J\)
\(Y_{i1}=(\mu + \alpha_1) + (b + c_1) x_{i1}+\epsilon_{i1}\) ⋯ \(Y_{iJ}=(\mu + \alpha_J) + (b + c_J) x_{iJ}+\epsilon_{iJ}\)


📌 Note: In this decomposition:

  • \((\alpha_j)_j\) represent the main effects of the factor, capturing how each cell’s intercept deviates from the reference.
  • \((c_j x_{ij})_j\) represent the interaction between the factor and the regressor, where the slopes for each cell \(j\) are allowed to vary by \(c_j\).

[Singular Model]
We define the linear Gaussian regression model (ANCOVA single-factor model) in its singular form as follows: \[\begin{equation*} \label{eq:Anova1_SM} \tag{Anova1 [SM]} Y_{ij}=(\mu + \alpha_j) + (b + c_j) x_{ij}+\epsilon_{ij},\quad i\in\{1,\ldots,n_j\}, \ j\in\mathcal{J} \end{equation*}\] where \[\epsilon_{ij}\stackrel{i.i.d.}{\sim}\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2).\]


Now, let’s express our singular ANCOVA single-factor modelin matrix form. Define:

  • \(\boldsymbol{Y}\in\mathbb{R}^n\) and \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\in\mathbb{R}^n\).
  • \(\forall j\in\mathcal{J}\), \(\textbf{x}_{\cdot j}=(x_{1j},\cdots,x_{n_jj})^T\in\mathbb{R}^{n_j}\).
  • \(\textbf{c}=(c_1,\ldots,c_J)^\top\in\mathbb{R}^J\)
  • \(\boldsymbol{\alpha}=(\alpha_1,\ldots,\alpha_J)^\top\in\mathbb{R}^J\)
  • \(\textbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^n\), \(D_\textbf{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times J}\), \(A\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times J}\) matrix, by \(\textbf{c}\in\mathbb{R}^J\) and \(\boldsymbol{\alpha}\in\mathbb{R}^J\) \(s.t.\)

\[ \textbf{x}= \begin{pmatrix} x_{\cdot 1} \\ \vdots\\ x_{\cdot J} \end{pmatrix},\quad D_\textbf{x}=\begin{pmatrix} x_{\cdot 1} & 0 & & \\ 0 & x_{\cdot 2}& & \vdots\\ \vdots & &\ddots&0\\ &&& x_{\cdot J} \end{pmatrix},\quad A=\begin{pmatrix} {\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_{n_1} & 0 & & \\ 0 & {\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_{n_2} & & \vdots\\ \vdots & &\ddots&0\\ &&& {\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_{n_J} \end{pmatrix}, \]

\[\mathbb{X}=[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \textbf{x}\ D_\textbf{x}]\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times(2+2J)}\quad\text{and}\quad\boldsymbol{\beta}=\begin{pmatrix} \mu \\ \boldsymbol{\alpha}\\ b\\ \textbf{c} \end{pmatrix}\in\mathbb{R}^{2J+2} \]

📌 Note: \(\text{Rank}(\mathbb{X})=2J\), indicating that it does not have full rank.


[Singular Model]
We define the linear Gaussian regression model (ANCOVA single-factor model) in its singular matrix form as follows: \[\begin{equation*} \label{eq:ANCOVA1_SM} \tag{ANCOVA1 [SM]} \boldsymbol{Y}=\mu{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n+A\boldsymbol{\alpha}+ \textbf{x}b+D_\textbf{x}\textbf{c}+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}=\mathbb{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}+\boldsymbol{\epsilon}. \end{equation*}\] where \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\sim\mathcal{N}(\boldsymbol{0}_n,\sigma^2\mathbf{I}_n)\)


2. Estimation of the Model

Regular Model (Full Rank Design Matrix)

In the case where \(\boldsymbol{X}\) is a full rank matrix, the estimation of the model parameters is defined as: \[ \widehat{\boldsymbol{\theta}} = \underset{\boldsymbol{\theta}\in \mathbb{R}^{2J}}{\arg \min} \|\boldsymbol{Y}-\boldsymbol{X}\boldsymbol{\theta}\|^2. \] The parameter estimates are given by \[ \widehat{\boldsymbol{\theta}} = (\boldsymbol{X}^\top \boldsymbol{X})^{-1} \boldsymbol{X}^\top \boldsymbol{Y}, \] which is unique due to the full rank of \(\boldsymbol{X}\).

Singular Model (Not Full Rank Design Matrix)

When the design matrix \(\mathbb{X}\) is not full rank, the estimation is given by: \[ \widehat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \in \underset{\boldsymbol{\beta}\in \mathbb{R}^{2J+2}}{\arg \min} \|\boldsymbol{Y}- \mathbb{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}\|^2. \]

The parameter estimate \(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}\) is not unique since \(\mathbb{X}\) is not full rank. To obtain a unique solution, a constraint must be imposed: \[ 2J+2 - \text{Rank}(\boldsymbol{X}) = 2J+2 - 2J = 2. \]

These constraints ensure that we can identify a specific solution among the infinite possibilities that arise due to the singularity of \(\mathbb{X}\).


📌 Note: For both models, the prediction is unique and can be expressed as:

\[ \widehat{\boldsymbol{Y}} = P_\boldsymbol{X}\boldsymbol{Y}= \boldsymbol{X}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}, \quad \widehat{\boldsymbol{Y}} = P_\mathbb{X}\boldsymbol{Y}= \mathbb{X}\widehat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}. \]


2.1. The Classic used constraints

1.\(\,\) Contrast treatment. The constraint by default is \(\alpha_1=c_1= 0\).

Ⓡ lm(mesure~alcool*AGE,data=marqueur)

2.\(\,\) For a fix \(k>1\), \(\alpha_k=c_k=0\) (choice of the cell \(k\) as the reference cell), just adjust using the relevel() function.
3.\(\,\) Contrast sum. \(\sum_{j=1}^J\alpha_j=\sum_{j=1}^Jc_j=0.\)

Ⓡ lm(mesure~alcool*AGE,contrasts=list(alcool="contr.sum"),data=marqueur)

4.\(\,\) Orthogonality constraint. \(\sum_{j=1}^Jn_j\alpha_j=\sum_{j=1}^Jn_jc_j=0\) not coded in Ⓡ so we need to implement it ourselves.

2.2. Theoretical results

Some notations

Empirical Mean Definition
Of observations \(Y_{ij}\) having the modality \(j\) \(\overline{Y}_{\cdot j}=\frac{1}{n_j}\sum_{i=1}^{n_j}Y_{ij}\)
Of all observations \(Y_{ij}\) \(\overline{Y}_{\cdot \cdot}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=1}^J\sum_{i=1}^{n_j}Y_{ij}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=1}^Jn_j\overline{Y}_{\cdot j}\)
Of all empirical means \(\overline{Y}_{\cdot j}\) \(\overline{\overline{Y}}_{\cdot \cdot }=\frac{1}{J}\sum_{j=1}^J\overline{Y}_{\cdot j}\)
Of all the observations \(x_{ij}\) \(\overline{x}_{\cdot j}=\frac{1}{n_j}\sum_{i=1}^{n_j}x_{ij}\)
Of order 2 of all the observations \(x_{ij}\) \(\overline{x^2}_{\cdot j}=\frac{1}{n_j}\sum_{i=1}^{n_j}x_{ij}^2\)
Of the observations \((x_{ij},Y_{ij})\) \(\overline{x_{\cdot j}Y_{\cdot j}}=\frac{1}{n_j}\sum_{i=1}^{n_j}x_{ij}Y_{ij}\)

[Proposition 5]
Let \(\mathcal{J} := \{1, \ldots, J\}\). Consider the linear Gaussian regression model (ANCOVA single-factor model) in its singular form. For the following constraints, the estimations are as follows

Model Constraints Estimators
Regular No constraints \(\widehat\tau_j=\frac{\overline{x^2}_{\cdot j}\overline Y_{\cdot j}- \overline x_{\cdot j}\overline {x_{\cdot j}Y_{\cdot j}}}{\overline{x^2}_{\cdot j}-(\overline{x}_{\cdot j})^2}\,\) and \(\,\widehat\beta_j=\frac{\overline {x_{\cdot j}Y_{\cdot j}}-\overline x_{\cdot j}\overline Y_{\cdot j} }{\overline{x^2}_{\cdot j}-(\overline{x}_{\cdot j})^2}\)
Singular \(\alpha_1=c_1=0\) \(\begin{cases} &\widehat\alpha_1=\widehat c_1=0\\ &\widehat \mu=\widehat\tau_1\\ &\widehat b=\widehat\beta_1 \end{cases}\) and \(\,\,\forall j\geq 2\) \(\begin{cases} &\widehat\alpha_j= \widehat\tau_j-\widehat\tau_1\\ &\widehat c_j = \widehat\beta_j-\widehat\beta_1 \end{cases}\)


📝 Here we will only give the case of constraint 1. For other constraints, a similar calculation is sufficient to find the result.

Sketch of proof. In the regular model, (OLSE) gives \(\widehat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}=(\boldsymbol{X}^T\boldsymbol{X})^{-1}\boldsymbol{X}^T\boldsymbol{Y}\) as \(\boldsymbol{X}\) is full rank. The \(\boldsymbol{X}^j\) are full rank \(2\) and \(\boldsymbol{X}\) matrix is diagonal by block,then \(\forall j\in \mathcal{J}\)

\[\begin{eqnarray*} \widehat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_j & = & \begin{pmatrix} \widehat\tau_j \\ \widehat\beta_j\\ \end{pmatrix}=\left((\boldsymbol{X}^j)^T\boldsymbol{X}^j\right)^{-1}(\boldsymbol{X}^j)^T\boldsymbol{Y}^j \end{eqnarray*}\]

As \(\widehat{Y}_{ij}\) is unique, it comes \[ \widehat Y_{ij}=\widehat \mu+\widehat\alpha_j+(\widehat b+\widehat c_j)x_{ij}=\widehat\tau_j+\widehat\beta_jx_{ij} \] The result is obtained using the constraint and by identification. \(\square\)

Unbiased estimator of \(\sigma^2\)


[Proposition 2]

Consider the linear Gaussian regression model (ANCOVA single-factor model) in its singular form under the posutlats [P1]–[P3]. For any classical constraint, an unbiased estimator of \(\sigma^2\) is \[\widehat\sigma^2=\frac{\|\boldsymbol{Y}-\widehat{\boldsymbol{Y}}\|^2}{n-2J}=\frac{1}{n-2J}\sum_{j=1}^J\sum_{i=1}^{n_j}(Y_{ij}- \widehat{Y}_{ij})^2,\] where \(\widehat{\boldsymbol{Y}}=P_\boldsymbol{X}\boldsymbol{Y}=P_\mathbb{X}\boldsymbol{Y}\)

Moreover, under the gaussian assumption [P4] \[\frac{(n-2J)\widehat\sigma^2}{\sigma^2}\sim\chi^2(n-2J).\]


Proof. Immediate according to previous Chapters.\(\square\)

📌 Note: Whether we consider the regular or the singular model, we have the equality of ranks: \[ \text{Rank}(\boldsymbol{X}) = \text{Rank}(\mathbb{X}) = 2J. \]

3. Tests

Let us define the different following models:

  • \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu}\,:\, Y=\mu{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n+\epsilon\)
  • \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha}\,:\, Y=\mu{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n+A\boldsymbol{\alpha}+\epsilon\)
  • \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu,b}\,:\, Y=\mu{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n+b\textbf{x}+\epsilon\)
  • \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b}\,:\, Y=\mu{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n+A\boldsymbol{\alpha}+bx+\epsilon\)
  • \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu,b,c}\,:\, Y=\mu{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n+b\textbf{x}+D_\textbf{x}c+\epsilon\)
  • \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b,c}\,:\, Y=\mu{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n+A\boldsymbol{\alpha}+b\textbf{x}+D_\textbf{x}c+\epsilon\)

where \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\sim\mathcal{N}(0_n,\sigma^2\mathbf{I}_n)\).

Type I Analysis. Here, the full model is represented by \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b,c}\). The line-by-line tests conducted in the anova analysis are \[ R_j^a =\{F_{j}^a>q^{ {\Large{\mathcal{F}}}_{d_j,n-2J} }_{1-\alpha}\},\quad \text{for}\quad j=1,\ldots,3 \]

and are summarized in the following table:

anova Tests F Value Fisher law
Line 1. \(\mathcal{H}_0 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu} \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, vs \,\, \mathcal{H}_1 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha}\) \(F_{1}^a=\|P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A]}Y-P_{1_n}Y\|^2/((J-1)\widehat\sigma^2)\) \({\Large{\mathcal{F}}}_{J-1,n-2J}\)
Line 2. \(\mathcal{H}_0 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha} \,\,\,\, vs \,\, \mathcal{H}_1 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b}\) \(F_{2}^a=\|P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}]}Y-P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A]}Y\|^2/\widehat{\sigma}^2\) \({\Large{\mathcal{F}}}_{1,n-2J}\)
Line 3. \(\mathcal{H}_0 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b} \,\, vs \,\, \mathcal{H}_1 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b,c}\) \(F_{3}^a=\|P_{[\mathbb{X}]}Y-P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}]}Y\|^2/((J-1)(K-1)\widehat\sigma^2)\) \({\Large{\mathcal{F}}}_{J-1,n-2J}\)


📌 Note: Recall, \(\widehat\sigma^2\) is calculated from the full model., i.e. here from \(\mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b,c}\), \(s.t.\) \[\widehat\sigma^2=\frac{\|\boldsymbol{Y}-P_{\mathbb{X}}\boldsymbol{Y}\|^2}{n-2J} \]

Sketch of proof.

First note that:

\(\begin{array}{ll} &\text{Rank}(\mathbb{X})= \text{Rank}([{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \textbf{x}\ D_\textbf{x}])=2J\\ &\text{Rank}({\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n)=1\\ &\text{Rank}([1_n \ A])=J\\ &\text{Rank}([{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ \,\textbf{x}])=2\\ &\text{Rank}([{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}])=J+1 \end{array}\)

Moreover,

\(\begin{array}{ll} &\text{Rank}(\mathbb{X})-\text{Rank}([{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}])=2J-(J+1)=J-1\\ &\text{Rank}([{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x})-\text{Rank}( [{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A])=(J+1)-J=1\\ &\text{Rank}([{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}])-\text{Rank}([1_n \ \,\textbf{x}])=(J+1)-2=J-1\\ &\text{Rank}([{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A])-\text{Rank}({\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n)=J-1 \end{array}\)

Recall that by proposition 4 \[\frac{(n-2J)\widehat\sigma^2}{\sigma^2}\sim\chi^2(n-2J). \]

Then, we conclude by the Nested theorem of the chapter 2.\(\square\)

and are summarized in the following table:

Anova Tests F Value Fisher law
Line 1. \(\mathcal{H}_0 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,b} \,\,\,\,\, vs \,\, \mathcal{H}_1 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b}\) \(F_{1}^A=\|P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}]}Y-P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ \, \textbf{x}]}Y\|^2/((J-1)\widehat\sigma^2)\) \({\Large{\mathcal{F}}}_{J-1,n-2J}\)
Line 2. \(\mathcal{H}_0 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha} \,\,\,\, vs \,\, \mathcal{H}_1 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b\beta}\) \(F_{2}^A=\|P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}]}Y-P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A]}Y\|^2/\widehat{\sigma}^2\) \({\Large{\mathcal{F}}}_{1,n-2J}\)
Line 3. \(\mathcal{H}_0 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b} \,\, vs \,\, \mathcal{H}_1 : \mathcal{M}_{\mu,\alpha,b,c}\) \(F_{3}^A=\|P_{[\mathbb{X}]}Y-P_{[{\Large{\mathbf{1}}}_n \ A \ \,\textbf{x}]}Y\|^2/((J-1)(K-1)\widehat\sigma^2)\) \({\Large{\mathcal{F}}}_{J-1,n-2J}\)

4. What about the full dataset ?

In this section, we will analyze the entire dataset by comparing various models using multiple approaches. The goal is to evaluate which model provides the best fit for the data when considering all available predictors: alcool, tabac, SEXE, AGE, taille, and poids. We begin by fitting two linear models: one with just the intercept (null model: MOD0) and another with all predictors included (MOD1).

MOD0<-lm(mesure~1,data=marqueur)
MOD1<-lm(mesure~alcool+tabac+ SEXE+AGE+taille+poids,data=marqueur)

Model selection using stepwise AIC To find the most relevant predictors, we apply stepwise selection using AIC (Akaike Information Criterion). This process helps to identify a simpler model that still explains the data well. We’ll perform both forward and backward selection methods and compare the selected models.

library(MASS)
modBoth<-stepAIC(MOD0, mesure~SEXE+AGE+taille+poids+tabac+alcool,trace=F, direction=c("both"))
#modForw<-stepAIC(MOD0, mesure~SEXE+AGE+taille+poids+tabac+alcool,trace=F, direction=c('forward'))
#modBack<-stepAIC(MOD1,~.,trace=F,direction=c("backward"))
# Anova(MOD1)

Model comparison We now compare three models using Fisher tests for nested models:

  1. The model selected via stepwise AIC (modBoth)
  2. A model based on alcool, AGE, and poids as predictors (MODanova)
  3. The full model with all predictors (MOD1)
MODanova <- lm(mesure ~ alcool + AGE + poids, data = marqueur) 
Comparaison<-c("modBoth vs MODanova","modBoth vs MODanova")
P_value<-c(anova(modBoth, MODanova)$`Pr(>F)`[2] ,anova(modBoth,MOD1)$`Pr(>F)`[2])
cbind.data.frame(Comparaison,P_value)

Finally, we extract the AIC values for the models to evaluate which one offers the best trade-off between model complexity and fit.

AIC(modBoth, MODanova, MOD1)

📈 The model chosen as the best fit for the data is modBoth.
